SIMPLE: exception
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exception
<hw>Ex*cep"tion</hw> <pr>(⟦ecr⟧k*s⟦ecr⟧p"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>exceptio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>exception</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of excepting or excluding; exclusion;
restriction by taking out something which would otherwise be included,
as in a class, statement, rule.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is excepted or taken out from others; a
person, thing, or case, specified as distinct, or not included; <as>as,
almost every general rule has its <ex>exceptions</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Such rare <qex>exceptions</qex>, shining in the dark,⟦br⟧
Prove, rather than impeach, the just remark.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>Often with <xex>to</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That proud <qex>exception</qex> to all nature's laws.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An objection, oral or written,
taken, in the course of an action, as to bail or security; or as to the
decision of a judge, in the course of a trail, or in his charge to a
jury; or as to lapse of time, or scandal, impertinence, or insufficiency
in a pleading; also, as in conveyancing, a clause by which the grantor
excepts something before granted.</def> <rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An objection; cavil; dissent; disapprobation;
offense; cause of offense; -- usually followed by <xex>to</xex> or
<xex>against</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will never answer what <qex>exceptions</qex> they can have
against our account [relation].</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He . . . took <qex>exception</qex> to the place of their
burial.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She takes <qex>exceptions</qex> at your person.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Bill of exceptions</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a
statement of exceptions to the decision, or instructions of a judge in
the trial of a cause, made for the purpose of putting the points decided
on record so as to bring them before a superior court or the full bench
for review.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exceptionable</ent>⟦br⟧
